00:02:22.270 --> 00:02:26.340
First, Marjorie Agosín
was born, I just learned,

00:02:26.340 --> 00:02:28.620 position:56%
very close to the Library of
Congress, right here in [inaudible],

00:02:28.620 --> 00:02:33.090
Maryland, but left
very, very early to live

00:02:33.090 --> 00:02:35.300
in Chile, where she was raised.

00:02:35.300 --> 00:02:38.540
Her family moved to the United
States soon before the coo

00:02:38.540 --> 00:02:42.330
that installed Augusto
Pinochet back to the states.

00:02:42.330 --> 00:02:45.210
Agosín earned her bachelor's
from the University of Georgia

00:02:45.210 --> 00:02:48.950
and a masters and a PhD
from Indiana University.

00:02:48.950 --> 00:02:51.750
Both her scholarship
and her creative work,

00:02:51.750 --> 00:02:57.190
she focuses on social justice,
feminism and remembrance.

00:02:57.190 --> 00:03:02.290
In 1986, Agosín published
the book, "Pablo Neruda,"

00:03:02.290 --> 00:03:05.410
as part of Twain's
world author's series,

00:03:05.410 --> 00:03:09.520
a series of literary criticisms,
offering in depth introductions

00:03:09.520 --> 00:03:12.650
to the lives and works of
writers, the history and influence

00:03:12.650 --> 00:03:15.160
of literary movements
and the development

00:03:15.160 --> 00:03:17.480
of literary of [inaudible].

00:03:17.480 --> 00:03:20.950
Agosín is the author of
numerous works of poetry,

00:03:20.950 --> 00:03:23.400
fiction and literary criticism.

00:03:23.400 --> 00:03:27.840
Her collection include The Angle of
Memory, The Alphabet in my Hands,

00:03:27.840 --> 00:03:31.300
a Ride in Life, Always
from somewhere else,

00:03:31.300 --> 00:03:35.950
a Memoir of my Chilean Jewish
father, An absence of shadows,

00:03:35.950 --> 00:03:40.200
Melodious Women and A
Crossroads and A Star Memoires

00:03:40.200 --> 00:03:43.860
of a Jewish girl in
Chile, among others.

00:03:43.860 --> 00:03:49.530
Agosín has received many honors
and awards for writing and work

00:03:49.530 --> 00:03:53.920
as a human rights activists
including a Jeanette Rankin award

00:03:53.920 --> 00:03:59.380 position:56%
in human rights and a United Nations
Leadership award for human rights.

00:03:59.380 --> 00:04:03.650
The Chilean government honored
her with a Gabriela Mistral Medal

00:04:03.650 --> 00:04:05.830
for lifetime achievement.

00:04:05.830 --> 00:04:11.430
Agosín is the Luella LeMer Slaner
professor in Latin American studies

00:04:11.430 --> 00:04:16.240
and a professor of Spanish
at Wellesley College.

00:04:16.240 --> 00:04:24.080
Forrest Gander was born in
California and grew up in Virginia

00:04:24.080 --> 00:04:25.960
and attended the college
of William and Mary

00:04:25.960 --> 00:04:27.990
where he majored in Geology.

00:04:27.990 --> 00:04:32.450 position:56%
After earning an MA in Literature
from San Francisco State University,

00:04:32.450 --> 00:04:36.520
Gander moved to Mexico, then
to Arkansas, where his poetry,

00:04:36.520 --> 00:04:40.330 position:56%
informed by his knowledge of Geology
turned its attention to landscape

00:04:40.330 --> 00:04:43.250
as foreground or source of action.

00:04:43.250 --> 00:04:47.480
He is the author of 13 poetry
collections and two novels,

00:04:47.480 --> 00:04:53.870
including "I against I, Torn Awake"
and "Science and Steeple Flower."

00:04:53.870 --> 00:04:58.930
He is the editor of Mouth to Mouth,
Twelve Contemporary Mexican Women,

00:04:58.930 --> 00:05:01.990
a Bilingual Anthology of
Contemporary Mexican Poets

00:05:01.990 --> 00:05:05.180
and the translator of No Shelter,

00:05:05.180 --> 00:05:08.640
the selected poems
of Pura Lopez Colome.

00:05:08.640 --> 00:05:11.400
Gander's critically
acclaimed translations

00:05:11.400 --> 00:05:16.530
of Pablo Neruda are included in The
Essential Neruda Selected Poems"

00:05:16.530 --> 00:05:22.460
from 2004 and in 2016, he
published a bilingual edition

00:05:22.460 --> 00:05:27.680
of Twenty Previously Unknown
and Unseen Neruda Poems,

00:05:27.680 --> 00:05:33.420
which are presenting here today,
then come back, The Lost Neruda.

00:05:33.420 --> 00:05:36.900
He won the Pen Translation
award for the book, The Night,

00:05:36.900 --> 00:05:39.930
by Bolivian poet, Jaime Sáenz.

00:05:39.930 --> 00:05:45.020
Gander has won the Reading Writers
Award, a Howard Foundation Award,

00:05:45.020 --> 00:05:48.890
the Jessica Novel Maxwell Memorial
Prize, two Gertrude Stein Awards

00:05:48.890 --> 00:05:52.930
for innovative North American
writing and fellowships

00:05:52.930 --> 00:05:56.650
from the National Endowment for
the Arts, the Guggenheim Foundation

00:05:56.650 --> 00:05:58.850
and the United States Artists.

00:05:58.850 --> 00:06:02.900
He has taught at Harvard and
Brown University and also last

00:06:02.900 --> 00:06:04.940
but not least, the man of the hour

00:06:04.940 --> 00:06:08.020
who is making all this
possible, Pablo Neruda.

00:06:08.020 --> 00:06:10.210
He's the author of more

00:06:10.210 --> 00:06:13.450
than 50 books including
The Poetry Collection,

00:06:13.450 --> 00:06:17.570
Veinte Poemas de Amor y una Cancion
desesperada, Twenty Love Poems

00:06:17.570 --> 00:06:22.850
and a Song of Despair, Residencia
en la Tierra, Residence on Earth

00:06:22.850 --> 00:06:26.570
and Alturas de Machupichu,
the Heights of Machupichu,

00:06:26.570 --> 00:06:31.130
as well as his autobiography,
Confieso que he Vivido Memorias.

00:06:31.130 --> 00:06:37.550
In 1971, Neruda was awarded
the noble prize for Literature.

00:06:37.550 --> 00:06:41.290
His other honors include The
National Prize for literature

00:06:41.290 --> 00:06:46.890
of Chile, the International Peace
Prize and the Stallion Peace Prize.

00:06:46.890 --> 00:06:49.550
Alongside a prolific
literary career,

00:06:49.550 --> 00:06:54.150
Neruda served as a Chilean diplomat
and sought a career in politics.

00:06:54.150 --> 00:06:58.790
In 1945, he was elected senator
of the republic as a member

00:06:58.790 --> 00:07:04.110
of the communist party, which
was outlawed four years later.

00:07:04.110 --> 00:07:08.830
The poet sought exile in Mexico
and later toured Europe and Asia.

00:07:08.830 --> 00:07:13.020
He returned to Santiago, Chile
in 1952 where he continued

00:07:13.020 --> 00:07:16.750
to write until his death in 1973.

